## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is the most popular men's bracelet style at Blue Nile?

The 8" Miami Cuban Link in 14k Yellow Gold at 6mm — 7 reviews at $2,225. It's the most reviewed piece on the men's page and the most widely recognized fine jewelry style in men's bracelets. If you're buying without a specific preference, start here.

### What width Miami Cuban link bracelet should I choose?

For most men, 6mm–7.3mm is the versatile everyday range. 9.3mm makes a clear statement and is the most common upgrade from 6mm. 11mm+ is a deliberate choice — worn by men who specifically want bold, heavy wrist presence. Measure your wrist before ordering anything over 9mm wide.

### Is the lab-grown diamond tennis bracelet worth buying?

For men's daily wear, yes — it's the strongest value on this page. Seven carats of F-G / VS2-SI1 lab diamonds in 14k white gold at $4,592 (30% off). The natural equivalent at similar quality costs three times more. Lab diamonds in four-prong settings are visually indistinguishable from natural at arm's length.

### What is the difference between natural and lab-grown diamond tennis bracelets at Blue Nile?

Price, origin, and quality grade. Natural: H-I color / SI1-SI2 clarity, $9,690–$24,750. Lab: F-G color / VS2-SI1 (one grade higher), $3,570–$10,507 at 30% off. Lab diamonds are physically and chemically identical to natural — the difference is where they formed. Natural retains more resale value (40–50% vs 10–20% for lab).

### How long should a men's bracelet be?

Standard is 8 inches — fits wrists from 6.5" to 7.5" with appropriate slack. Wrist over 7.5": look for 8.5" or the 9" Cuban option. For wide chains (9mm+), add 0.5" extra.

### Can I wear a gold bracelet at the gym or in the pool?

Gold doesn't rust, but chlorine degrades 14k gold alloy over time by dissolving the alloy metals. Remove fine gold before swimming and gym workouts. A rigid Cuban link will also catch on equipment. Daily office and social wear is fine indefinitely.

### What is the difference between 14k and 18k gold for a men's bracelet?

14k is 58.3% pure gold, harder and more scratch-resistant. 18k is 75% pure gold — heavier feel, richer color, slightly softer metal. For a Cuban worn daily, 14k is the right choice for durability. The Blue Nile Signature Tennis is in platinum — higher density than gold, maximum prong security for the diamonds.

### What is a Figaro chain bracelet?

A Figaro chain alternates link sizes — typically two or three short round links followed by one longer oval link, repeating. The pattern creates visual rhythm that distinguishes it from plain curb or rope chains. It's one of the oldest Italian gold chain patterns, named after the 18th-century opera character Figaro.

### Should I choose platinum or 14k gold for a men's tennis bracelet?

For a tennis bracelet: platinum holds four-prong settings more securely over time (higher density = stronger prong retention) and never requires rhodium plating like white gold. The trade-off is cost. For a Cuban link: 14k yellow gold is the traditional and most common choice — platinum Cubans exist but are far less common and the yellow gold aesthetic is part of the style's identity.

### Are Blue Nile gold bracelets genuine fine jewelry?

Yes. Every bracelet on Blue Nile's men's page is stamped with its karat mark (14K, 18K, or Platinum) and comes with documentation. Blue Nile is a GIA-accredited retailer. If you want independent verification after purchase, any local jeweler can test gold karat in under five minutes.

### What is the Blue Nile Signature Ideal Cut Tennis Bracelet?

It's Blue Nile's highest-quality natural diamond tennis bracelet — each stone is Ideal Cut for maximum light return, not the standard H-I/SI1-SI2 used in the regular tennis range. At ~~$40,570~~ $36,513 for 7ct in platinum, it is investment-tier fine jewelry. Worth it only for buyers who specifically need Ideal Cut documentation and platinum construction.

### How do I care for a gold chain bracelet?

Store each chain separately — gold scratches gold. Clean periodically with warm soapy water and a soft brush, rinse thoroughly, dry completely. Keep away from chlorine, perfumes, and hairspray applied directly to the bracelet. For wide Cubans, check the clasp mechanism every few months — the box clasp on heavy chains wears faster than the chain itself.

